MSTR has increased the bitcoin it owns this year by about 33 and has increased its current share count roughly 15 through convertible debt offers resulting in a current increase of BTC per share of about 18 YTD. If it continues at this rate in 4 years the amount of Bitcoin it holds per share doubles. In 10 years BTC per share is 6x higher. If this happens owning MicroStrategy will give a shareholder more bitcoin than if they just bought a ETF. This is the chance holders are taking. So they are basically taking on low interest debt and buying bitcoin giving them leverage to the price of bitcoin in both directions. Many institutions that are limited to only investing in bonds want to lend money to MicroStrategy because it offers much better returns than government bonds or any other bonds. The other thing to remember is they have a software business that is working on developing bitcoin applications and have a goal of becoming a bank as well. So the premium to net asset value also reflects the chance that any of these ventures will be profitable, much like how many magnificent 7 companies are worth 3050x times current earnings in a year. If inflation continues to accelerate and BTC continues its trend over the past 15 years MSTR will possibly be the largest company in the world in 1020 years. If bitcoin stagnates for longer than a 4 year period they could go bankrupt. If BTC starts doing 10 a year average and doesnt have any explosive years like in the past MSTR might do ok but a Bitcoin ETF would likely out preform it. This is the chance investors are taking.

There is still no clear relationship between bitcoin and its price. It does not get cash from any operations like a company does. The value of a company is the present value of the cash flows that the company will earn in its lifetime. The fact that those cash flows are in the future means that we dont know what they are, we can only make educated guesses, which is why the stock price is random to a degree. Bitcoin has no future cash flows. It is an asset with a price because people think it has value, just like goldsilverbeanie babies. The technology behind bitcoin is very real, and will one day maybe lead to some new change, but the price is a question mark. There is no clear relationship. It has the price that it does because people are willing to pay for it and thats it.

Depends on whether its a traditional or Roth 401k or some combination. With the Roth you paid your taxes up front so later when you withdraw, that doesnt count as income. With Traditional its the other way around the money you contributed wasnt counted as income so it wasnt taxed, but the withdrawals will be. Many companies now allow employee contributions to follow either ruleset, but employer contributions are almost always Traditional employer Roth contributions are allowed but should probably be optin because that increases the employees tax burden. So you may have some of both, depends what you chose when setting up your 401k contributions.

This is why I dont look at returns for anything on less than a 5 year timeline. 9 months during a booming market is a terrible metric when evaluating investments.

Selling naked puts will work right up until it zeroes out your account or worse dont pick up pennies in front of a steamroller. With respect you should not be selling options unless you actually know what youre doing with heding and risk management. It can go fantastically wrong very quickly. If you want an alternative to vegas or the lottery, buying options can be fun for some people who arent professionals but certainly dont stake any more than youd be fine losing.

Selling covered calls is a conservative strategy that is expected to reduce both risks and returns, compared to just holding the underlying asset. The seller will probably see lots of small wins get the premium and keep the stock a few large losses get the premium and have to sell the stock at a below market price that will more than offset the wins. Both strategies are likely to make money buying holding is likely to make more. Check the returns of any ETF that uses this strategy compare them to the returns of the assets they own youll see this.

I generally dont buy options except as a hedge. I dont bet on future price direction but I do try to profit off the premium created by those who do. This is not selling naked calls, the risks are definably limited. When I sell puts, its always against a stock I would want in my portfolio and in quantity and price my portfolio can afford if put. Could it go to 0? Sure, any stock could, but that doesnt make it Vegas. I have been put stock on occasion, then my cost basis is lower than the outright purchase of the underlying stock would have been. If the stock price is above strike at expiry, I pocket the premium and move on. I have a common position in LRCX today i was put from 2018 that is up 5x my base price, which includes the premium I sold back then. And, yes, the position was under water at the time, as it would have been had I purchased the stock. In this case, in the long run, I made out way better than whoever put me the shares of this phenomenal company.

I am a long term investor with decades of experience and held a Series 7 decades ago, straight out of college BS Econ. If i get put on the common, its generally in one I want to take a position in or add to. If the price runs up and away, I am rewarded with the premium. I win either way, i never get too far out over my skis on this strategy and it represents single digit percentages of my equity positions, which are mostly LT.

Again, with covered calls, the issue is not that the seller is likely to lose money. The issue is that theyre likely to make less money than they would by buying holding the same assets. The premiums are not magic free money, despite what some claim.

Then there's Satoshi's 1.1 million on the Genesis block, and probably more lost keys in the future. I have been buying btc since 2017.  When MSTR took $500 million and bought btc in 2020 i bought it at $160 (pre-10x split)  for my retirement account.   At that time the company was valued at 1.5 billion.  I held on and saw it rise during the bull market in  bitcoin a few months later.  As you should remember bitcoin topped out at 20K.  MSTR rose temporarily to $1300 per share in 2021.  Then bitcoin winter hit.  MSTR hit a low of $20 in 2022.  I took profits at $800 before the crash.  MSTR then was basically worth as much as their bitcoin holdings.  I think it got as low as $5000 per bitcoin.  I bought back in to MSTR around $300 per share and held till this year.  During that 4-5 year time frame MSTR was valued at approx 1.3 of its bitcoin value.  Or a premium of approximately 30%.  That was the basis for many years.  Right now if you buy MSTR for its bitcoin holdings you are paying 270% premium.  This stock unfortunately has turned into a classic "pump and dump"  The pros are pushing it way  higher using momentum .  As always in the stock market the public buys at the top and sells at the bottom.  Bitcoin will still continue to appreciate long term but MSTR will fall within the next few months by at least 50-60%.   If you really want Bitcoin buy an ETF.  Schwab will let you buy IBIT.  No premium.  You will be kicking yourself if Bitcoin gets to $200K and MSTR is below today's price.  Don't be fooled.  Stay away.  It was a great value.  Not anymore.

Microsoft Corp. (NASDAQ:MSFT), with a market capitalization of over $3 trillion, disclosed it will vote for an assessment of investing in Bitcoin (CRYPTO: BTC) during the upcoming shareholders meeting in December.

What happened: In a Thursday filing with the SEC, the technology giant listed a line item “Assessment of Investing in Bitcoin” for a vote in the annual meeting on Dec. 10.

The submission stated that the Board advises voting against this plan.

The shareholders requested the board conduct the assessment, citing Bitcoin's healthy gains—nearly 100% over the last year and 414% in the last five years. 

The proposal mentioned MicroStrategy Inc. (NASDAQ:MSTR), a technology company that holds a large chunk of Bitcoin on its balance sheet and whose shares have outperformed Microsoft in 2024. While Microsoft shares have shot up 14.52% so far in 2024, MicroStrategy shares have shot up a whopping 244%.

Additionally, attention was called to Microsoft's second-largest shareholder, BlackRock, which operates iShares Bitcoin Trust ETF (NASDAQ:IBIT), the largest Bitcoin-based investment fund. 

The shareholders called Bitcoin an "excellent," if not the best hedge against inflation.

October's Bitcoin options expiry, valued at $4.2 billion, is set for Friday. Of this, BTC options worth over $682 million, or 16.3% of the total, are poised to expire "in the money," predominantly as call options. This situation may lead to market volatility as holders of these profitable options decide whether to settle or adjust their positions for the next expiry cycle.The put-to-call open interest ratio for Bitcoin currently stands at 0.62, suggesting a relatively bullish sentiment. This means that for every 100 call options active, there are 62 put options open.The critical price point is $64,000, where the majority of options would expire worthless, resulting in the greatest loss for option buyers and the highest gain for option writers.

Increasing liquidity at this level provides a massive tailwind for investors to cushion uncertainty over tax increases and/or tariffs in 2025. Historically, large liquidity injections are associated with looser financial conditions such as lower bond yields, a weaker dollar, and long duration assets outperforming. The reason this is happening is because the US government will hit the debt ceiling on January 1st. When that happens, the government can no longer issue net new debt until Congress raises the debt ceiling later in the year (likely July). Instead, Treasury pays its bills through the Treasury General Account (TGA), which is likely to hold $700bn on January 1st . As such, TGA funds, which are held at the Federal Reserve and outside the banking sector, will be transferred into the banking system, boosting bank reserves, all else being equal (sounds like QE, but from the Treasury). The net effect is a consistent stream of liquidity being pumped into financial markets.

Short interest in MicroStrategy (MSTR) remained above 20% from early March to mid-June before significantly decreasing in the third quarter, even dipping below 10% in early August. The bearish sentiment rebounded to the high teens throughout much of September's second half as the stock price increased. However, as the rally intensified, short sellers rapidly exited their positions. This week, the short interest in MicroStrategy as a percentage of the free float decreased from 17% to approximately 16%, and the days-to-cover ratio reduced from 3.3 to 2.7, accompanied by a substantial increase in trading volume. Over the five-day period ending Thursday, the stock rose by 5.5%, and including Friday's 12% surge—fueled by the recent spike in bitcoin prices to late-July levels—MicroStrategy's stock has now climbed 89% from its September 6 low.

MicroStrategy Inc (MSTR). founder Michael Saylor encouraged those who doubt the upside potential of Bitcoin to go short on the company's stock, assuring that it would never sell the cryptocurrency. During an interview with journalist Madison Reidy that aired Thursday, Saylor asked skeptics to "love" MicroStrategy if they really "hate" Bitcoin."We’re the perfect instrument to short because I promise you, I won’t sell it. We’re going to be leveraged long on Bitcoin," said Saylor, one of the most passionate advocates of the cryptocurrency.“I want you to love us if you really hate BTC.”Saylor said as a company, MicroStrategy has been consistent and transparent in its policy of buying and holding on to Bitcoin, and it was up to market participants to decide if they wanted to buy, sell, or short their shares."When I was a younger man I would have been concerned about people shorting my stock but now I’m not," Saylor added. Saylor’s remarks came amid MicroStratgy’s audacious Bitcoin gambit, which has transformed the software development firm into a proxy for the world’s greatest digital asset. MicroStrategy adopted Bitcoin as its primary reserve asset in 2020, becoming the first publicly listed company to pursue this strategy, and hasn't looked back since then. Today, it holds over $17 billion of its total capital in Bitcoin, according to bitcointreasuries.net.

MicroStrategy's stock has surged in the past with Bitcoin gains in price, yet recently MSTR has surged while bitcoin's price has languished, escalating an untenable situation. The bitcoin value implied by MicroStrategy's stock now exceeds a 2.5 NAV premium, which is 2.5 times the actual spot price of bitcoin. The era when MicroStrategy's shares were a unique method for accessing bitcoin has passed momentarily. Nowadays, bitcoin can be easily acquired through brokerages, crypto exchanges, and, more recently, low-fee ETPs and ETFs. Historical trading patterns and logical reasoning indicate that the current excessive premium is likely to decrease, as it has in the past, presenting an attractive opportunity for a temporary short. FYI: I am NOT short. I am just saying that there is an opportunity for it, but I'm currently on the sidelines, expecting a lower price.

Nick Szabo, a computer scientist and legal scholar, created Bit Gold in 1998. While Bit Gold was not implemented, it is recognized as one of the initial efforts to establish a decentralized digital currency and is frequently seen as a forerunner to Bitcoin.Nick Szabo is recognized for introducing the concept of smart contracts in 1994. These are self-executing contracts with the terms of the agreement embedded within the code. Smart contracts have become an essential element of blockchain technology and are extensively utilized in numerous applications today.There has been speculation that Nick Szabo could be the enigmatic creator of Bitcoin, Satoshi Nakamoto, due to the parallels between Bit Gold and Bitcoin. The max pain point for Bitcoin is projected at $59,000, which could exert downward pressure on prices. Bitcoin sellers have become scarce, even as prices remain within 15% of the all-time highs. The sell-side risk is now at its lowest point since early 2024 and has reached a "minimum zone."Despite recent episodes of abrupt selloffs amid BTC price fluctuations, there seems to be little inclination for widespread selling. There has been a significant decline in potential sellers since the March all-time high for BTC/USD. After the peak of $73K, the number of individuals looking to sell Bitcoin has fallen to a minimum over the last six months.The sell-side risk ratio, which aggregates daily onchain realized profits and losses and divides them by Bitcoin's realized cap, offers a measure of possible selling pressure. Presently, its values are under 20,000, a stark contrast to the nearly 80,000 recorded during the peak in March.Bitcoin speculators, also known as short-term holders (STHs), are presently "in the black" following a prolonged period of uncertainty, which led to them distributing their holdings to the market, frequently at a loss. Bitcoin's price fell below $60,000 on Wednesday, dampening the initial enthusiasm following anticipated Federal Reserve interest-rate cuts. In the last 24 hours, Bitcoin declined by 3.6% to $59,848, marking a 12% decrease over three months and now trading 20% below its nearly $74,000 peak in March.The specific causes of the downturn were not immediately apparent, though profit-taking by traders after Fed Chair Jerome Powell's speech at Jackson Hole, which sparked a temporary rally in cryptocurrencies, could be a contributing factor.Powell indicated that the central bank is likely to begin reducing interest rates in September. Typically, lower rates are seen as favorable for cryptocurrencies, offering investors potentially higher returns compared to low-risk assets like government bonds.Despite an initial surge following Powell's comments, Bitcoin's Wednesday losses have erased all gains made since the Fed chair's address to monetary policymakers in Wyoming.Additionally, Bitcoin is experiencing the effects of low trading volume, with late August traditionally being a slow period for markets. This week, trading activity has slowed as investors await Nvidia's quarterly earnings report.The market seems to be primarily affected by automatic stop orders activated during periods of low trading volume, which often force leveraged traders to exit but can also entice long-term investors looking for opportunities to buy during price dips.

I find that confusion often arises over whether Bitcoin is or isn't a hedge against inflation due to misunderstandings concerning the time horizon of said inflation. Many people think of inflation as something that spikes for a year or two and usually gets under control by the FED relatively quickly. In this perspective, if Bitcoin were used as an inflation hedge, its price would rise in anticipation of further inflation and decrease as inflation worries fell. If you think in a Bitcoin standard and acknowledge the shortcomings of the FIAT system, it becomes evident that debasement and inflation are persistent issues. Although they may surge in certain years, these problems are continuous and do not find complete resolution within the FIAT framework. If one considers inflation to be a persistent issue, sustained by unrestrained fiscal policy and money printing, then Bitcoin could indeed serve as a long-term hedge against inflation over decades, not just for a brief span.

FWIW, if you're interested in Buffett (& Munger) Snowball is, I think, widely regarded as the best book. He gave Alice Schroeder access to anything she wanted (files, friends, etc), encouraged her, if she found "two sides" to a particular story, to write the version more unflattering to him. He would later regret this.Five years of research and writing, over 800 pages. A great achievement. If I had read this first, there'd have been no need to read the others.Alice wrote what nobody else could or would. He then disowned her because I guess it's tough to look in the mirror and then to have that reflection broadcast to the world. There are more sides to Buffett than just the cheerful, folksy, old sage.
